<p content-type="flushleft" class="p">The LAF of a storm characteristic is defined as
 <disp-formula id="eqs1" class="disp-formula">
  <math id="mes1" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mtext class="mtext">LAF</mtext>
    <mo class="mo">=</mo>
    <mfrac class="mfrac">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mtext class="mtext">Future</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">value</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">for</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">given</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">return</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">period</mtext>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mtext class="mtext">Modern</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">value</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">for</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">given</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">return</mtext>
      <mo class="mo"> </mo>
      <mtext class="mtext">period</mtext>
     </mrow>
    </mfrac>
    <mo class="mo">.</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
  <label class="label">[S1]</label>
 </disp-formula>Thus, an LAF &gt;1 indicates an increase in the magnitude of the quantity for a given return period in the future, while an LAF &lt;1 indicates a decrease in the magnitude of the quantity for a given return period in the future. 
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="sfig01" class="xref">Fig. S1</xref> shows LAFs of modern return periods for storm RMW and maximum wind values.
</p>
